{
  "query": "What evidence exists for the effectiveness of different strategies to combat white-nose syndrome in bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Treating bats for white-nose syndrome with a probiotic bacterium was evaluated in two randomized, controlled studies: one in Canada and one in the USA (2008). In Canada, treatment at the time of infection increased survival for little brown bats within laboratory cages and reduced disease symptoms; treatment 21 days prior to infection did not increase survival and was associated with worse symptoms (2008). In the USA, treatment within a mine increased survival for free-flying little brown bats, but survival of caged bats and disease severity did not differ from untreated bats (2008).\n- Breeding bats in captivity to supplement wild populations affected by white-nose syndrome has no studies evaluating its effects (2009).\n- Decontaminating clothing and equipment after entering caves to reduce spread of the pathogen has no studies evaluating effects on bat populations (2006).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2008",
    "2009",
    "2006"
  ]
}

